<br>
Yeah, it is a pretty painless process.  You know what was going on during that 10 minute wait though?  FBI was being contacted (computer or phone-line...depending on how "modern" the local authorities are) and you are checked vs. NCIC (I think that's what the guy told me...NCIC, or some other fancy acronym that means "a whole lotta info on yours and everyone else's ass".)<br>
<br>
I'm just wondering where "retardedly easy" came into it all.  To me, "retardedly easy" would be, I walk in, put down cash, collect my new weapon, a buttload of ammo, and get two Slim-Jims and a ski-mask at the "Impulse Buy" rack near the register.  Being checked against a criminal database, and having ID checked isn't difficult, and not something I will squawk about.  To me, however, the implication in "retardedly easy" was "any violent felon on PCP could get an AK-47 with the silver-dollar mod and industrial springs at the corner 7-11", so I figured I'd better ask for clarification.<br>
<br>
I, like you, found the purchase of a firearm to be relatively simple.  Living in a more rural state helps that quite a bit, but even here I would not entirely classify it as "retardedly easy". <p>Faust<BR>
